he right and left common iliac arteries. This bifurcation is a key anatomical landmark in the abdominal region.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EL1\u003C/strong\u003E, \u003Cstrong\u003EL2\u003C/strong\u003E, and \u003Cstrong\u003EL3\u003C/strong\u003E are too high, whilst \u003Cstrong\u003EL5\u003C/strong\u003E is too low as by this level, the common iliac arteries have already branched off.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EKnowing the vertebral level of the aortic bifurcation is useful knowledge for specific procedures, as well as for interpreting radiological images of the abdomen and pelvis. For example, during abdominal aortic aneurysm repair, precise knowledge of the aortic bifurcation is crucial to avoid complications.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The descending aorta ends at L4.","At L4, the descending aorta bifurcates into the common iliac arteries."],"references":["Netter, F. H. Netter Atlas of Human Anatomy: Classic Regional Approach-Ebook. 2022. Elsevier Health Sciences","Shahoud JS, Miao JH, Bolla SR. Anatomy, Thorax, Heart Aorta. [Updated 2023 Jul 24]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK538140/","Jacob, S. (2007). Human anatomy: a clinically-orientated approach. Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95971"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14518"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95971","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/95971"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-14T15:57:35+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-14T15:57:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7213"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113956"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emo